INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '237f9eea-2b8a-4b55-9474-0884de1fc43e',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Cassandra Query Optimization — TRACING ON, Slow Query Logs, and Killing N+1s$escape$,
  $escape$Cassandra has no EXPLAIN ANALYZE — your equivalent is `TRACING ON` in cqlsh. It dumps a full execution trace per coordinator and replica, exposing which SSTables were touched, tombstone counts, and wait times per stage. Run it against your CQL query, then look for high `sstables` values or tombstone warnings — both signal a partition that needs compaction or a TTL audit.

For persistent slow query logging, set `slow_query_log_timeout_in_ms: 500` in `cassandra.yaml`. Queries exceeding that threshold appear in `system.log` with full CQL text and latency. Pair with `nodetool tablehistograms <keyspace> <table>` to see read latency percentiles at the SSTable level.

The N+1 pattern in Cassandra is fetching a list of partition keys, then issuing individual `SELECT` statements per key in a loop. Fix it with a single `SELECT ... WHERE partition_key IN (?, ?, ?)` — Cassandra fans the request out to the correct replicas in parallel. Never use `ALLOW FILTERING` as a workaround; it forces a full cluster scan and bypasses the partition key entirely.$escape$,
  $escape$-- Enable tracing in cqlsh
TRACING ON;

SELECT * FROM events WHERE user_id = 'abc-123';
-- Output includes: sstables touched, tombstones scanned, read latency per stage

TRACING OFF;

-- N+1 anti-pattern
-- BAD: loop of individual reads per partition key
-- SELECT * FROM events WHERE user_id = ?;  -- called 100x in application code

-- GOOD: single fan-out read
SELECT event_id, event_type, created_at
FROM events
WHERE user_id IN ('abc-123', 'def-456', 'ghi-789');$escape$,
